I'm hesitant to post this review because it only brings attention to a new, "trendy" eating space in  a quiet and familial neighborhood. Places like Yafa are markers of gentrification in a mostly Latino and East Asian neighborhood. That being said, I have to respect Yafa for having reasonable prices. Their hibiscus tea was $3 when normally it would be $5-7 anywhere else. They did however tell me that the last order of lamb had already been given away right after I paid for mine. I instead got a chicken and rice dish which was very good, but a dish that I could perhaps make myself. All in all Yafa has great flavors but I probably won't frequent it very much as there are dozens of other local staples in the neighborhood that deserve as much attention. The breakfast here is delicious though

I had high hopes after reading the rave reviews and I wasn't disappointed. The food is excellent and moderately priced and the selection of fresh juices, coffee, and the teas are second to none. I had the Yafa fried chicken sandwich with homemade potato chips and it was flavorful and crispy. I highly recommend it. The blend of Yemeni spiced fried chicken with the plum chipotle sauce made for a wonderful combination. And to top it off, the brussel sprout cole slaw gave it that summertime cookout flavor. Whether you're trying to get a quick bite or lounge around and sip on rare international coffee, Yafa Cafe has you covered.

YEMEN 🇾🇪 Excerpt from Eat the World NYC: A few months ago, a space that used to be a Chinese takeout restaurant started to come alive with signs of life after a fairly quick renovation. A few doors down from Yemeni-owned Yafa Newsstand & Deli, which has served the corner of 4th Avenue and 45th Street for many years, Yafa Café has now been born.  For the better part of a couple months, only drinks were offered, but an open kitchen and the eager stories of its new operators (from the same family as the Yafa Deli) promised a marriage of foods from Brooklyn and Yemen, an exciting proposition.  When the sandwich board finally announced that breakfast and lunch were being served, the former was the goal on a first pass. Along with oats, bagels, and a gussied up bacon, egg and cheese sandwich lives the Yemeni breakfast ($10), which revolves around their excellent flaky traditional flatbread called khubz and a variety of "breakfast dips."
